From: Jiri Bohac <jbohac@suse.cz>
References: bsc#1197439
Subject: kvm: prevent kvm_clock time-warps
Patch-mainline: no, fixed by 09ec54429c6d10f87d1f084de53ae2c1c3a81108

Commit d8bb6f4c1670 ("x86: tsc prevent time going backwards") in v2.6.26 
fixes an issue in the TSC clocksource where and underflow can result in huge 
time warps.

kvm_clock is based on the same hardware TSC but never had this fix, until
commit 09ec54429c6d ("clocksource: Move cycle_last validation to core code") in
v3.17 moved the TSC fix higher to the timekeeper code, where it also works for
kvm_clock.

For v3.0, let's duplicate the fix from read_tsc() in kvm_clock_get_cycles().

Signed-off-by: Jiri Bohac <jbohac@suse.cz>


diff --git a/arch/x86/kernel/kvmclock.c b/arch/x86/kernel/kvmclock.c
index 6a726a385457..486101a72cd8 100644
--- a/arch/x86/kernel/kvmclock.c
+++ b/arch/x86/kernel/kvmclock.c
@@ -80,9 +80,18 @@ static cycle_t kvm_clock_read(void)
 	return ret;
 }
 
+static struct clocksource kvm_clock;
+
+/*
+ * kvm_clock is TSC-based and a similar risk of underflow and a time-warp
+ * is present as with the tsc clocksource. See the description of read_tsc().
+ */
 static cycle_t kvm_clock_get_cycles(struct clocksource *cs)
 {
-	return kvm_clock_read();
+	cycle_t ret = kvm_clock_read();
+
+	return ret >= kvm_clock.cycle_last ?
+		ret : kvm_clock.cycle_last;
 }
 
